msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/bsd-init.txt:481
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"3.2 Creating extra scripts\n"
"--------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/bsd-init.txt:489
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   As you probably know, it is common to have a /etc/rc.d/rc.local file "
"where\n"
" you put commands in that will be executed at the very end of the boot "
"process.\n"
" You can use it to create up-to-date issue files or to pick a random\n"
" message of the day. But since you created all bootscripts yourself,\n"
" you can change them as much as you like, and you probably won't need this\n"
" script. So what's it going to be?\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/bsd-init.txt:493
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   I personally recommend you create this script, for the purpose of\n"
" portability. Many daemons write one or two lines to this file, and it "
"saves\n"
" you trouble if it's already present. This is how you create one:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/bsd-init.txt:495
#, no-wrap
msgid "   Put this in a file /etc/rc.d/rc.local:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/bsd-init.txt:499
msgid ""
"-------------------------------/etc/rc.d/rc.local---------------------------- "
"#!/bin/sh -----------------------------end "
"/etc/rc.d/rc.local--------------------------"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/bsd-init.txt:501
#, no-wrap
msgid "  And make it executable:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/bsd-init.txt:503
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tchmod 754 /etc/rc.d/rc.local\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/bsd-init.txt:506
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   It is very easy for you to disable /etc/rc.d/rc.local; just remove\n"
" the executable flag from the script and it will be skipped at boot time.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/bsd-init.txt:512
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" When I showed you the synopsis of rc.d/, I also told you that you can\n"
" create extra files. You might put your iptables/ipchains lines for your\n"
" firewall into rc.firewall and call it from rc.{2,3}, or you may stuff\n"
" all daemons essential to NFS into rc.nfs and call that from another\n"
" script called rc.netdaemons, in which you start all networking daemons.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/bsd-init.txt:515
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"     Do what you like best - BSD init is IMHO closer to human thinking\n"
" than SysVInit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/bsd-init.txt:522
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   As a final tip in this section, I would like to point out to you that I\n"
" have often had a multi-user environment without networking. It would be a\n"
" good practice for you to set up this environment on, for example, runlevel "
"5\n"
" and set it up in a secure way. This implies you have to decide whether "
"you\n"
" really need a service or not, to avoid any damage that may be caused by "
"your\n"
" ignorance.\n"
msgstr ""

